{{Infobox stadium | stadium_name = Roberts Stadium | nickname = | image = Roberts Stadium.jpg | fullname = Myslik Field at Roberts Stadium<ref name="Roberts Stadium"/> | location = [[Princeton, NJ]] 08540 | coordinates = {{Coord|40.342343|-74.653965|display=inline, title}} | broke_ground = May, 2007 | built = | opened = September 2, 2008 | renovated = | expanded = | closed = | demolished = | owner = [[Princeton University]] | operator = Princeton University | surface = [[Grass]] | construction_cost = $8.4 million | architect = Anderson Architects<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.andersonarch.com/projects|title=Project List|publisher=Anderson Architects|accessdate=August 9, 2017}}</ref> | structural engineer = | services engineer = | general_contractor = Fitzpatrick & Associates, Inc<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fitzpatricknj.com/gallery/index.php|title=Gallery|publisher=Fitzpatrick & Associates|accessdate=August 9, 2017}}</ref> | project_manager = | main_contractors = | former_names = | tenants = [[Princeton Tigers#Soccer|Princeton Tigers Men's & Women's Soccer]] ([[NCAA]]) (2008-present) | seating_capacity = 2,356 | dimensions = 120 x 75 yards<ref>{{cite web|url=https://facilities.princeton.edu/projects/roberts-stadium-2008|title=Roberts Stadium|publisher=Princeton University|accessdate=August 9, 2017}}</ref> | scoreboard = }}
'''Roberts Stadium''' is a 2,356 seat [[soccer-specific stadium]] located on the [[campus]] of [[Princeton University]] in [[Princeton, New Jersey]]. It is the home to the [[Princeton Tigers#Soccer|Princeton Tigers men's and women's soccer teams]].<ref>{{cite news|title=SportsShorts|volume=108|url={{Google books|hCJbAAAAYAAJ|title=SportsShorts|53|plainurl=yes}}|publisher=Princeton Alumni Weekly|date=September 26, 2007}}</ref> The stadium is named in honor of Thomas S. Roberts '85, a former Princeton goal keeper. The stadium's natural [[grass]] game field, '''Myslik Field''', is named in memory of Robert H. Myslik '90, a soccer alumnus and assistant coach who died in 2003.<ref name="Roberts Stadium">{{cite web|title=Roberts Stadium • Home of Princeton Soccer|url=http://www.goprincetontigers.com/facilities/?id=6|accessdate=9 August 2017}}</ref> The team's [[artificial turf]] practice field, Plummer Field, is adjacent to the stadium.<ref name="Roberts Stadium"/>
Roberts Stadium opened September 2, 2008, and was formally dedicated October 4, 2008, following a doubleheader with [[Dartmouth College]]. The stadium replaced the former Lourie-Love Field, which stood on the same grounds. Lourie-Love Field was named after Princeton [[American football|football]] [[alumni]] [[Donold B. Lourie]] and [[George H. Love]], both 1922 graduates.
In May 2010, the [[United States men's national soccer team]] held a week-long pre-[[2010 FIFA World Cup|World Cup]] [[training camp]] at Roberts Stadium.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goprincetontigers.com/news/2010/5/27/204951756.aspx|title=THE TIES THAT BIND: THE U.S. MEN'S NATIONAL TEAM AND PRINCETON|publisher=goprincetontigers.com|date=May 27, 2010|accessdate=August 9, 2017}}</ref> In June 2012, the [[United States women's national soccer team]] held a two week-long training camp at the stadium to prepare for an [[international friendly]] against the [[China women's national football team|Chinese women's national football team]] at [[Talen Energy Stadium]] in [[Chester, PA]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goprincetontigers.com/news/2012/6/28/205499382.aspx|title=U.S. WOMEN'S NATIONAL TEAM'S VISIT, FROM A PLAYER'S VIEW|publisher=goprincetontigers.com|date=June 28, 2012|accessdate=August 9, 2017}}</ref>
